{"id":"1804.07446","submitter":"Harry Altman","authors":"Harry Altman","title":"Integer complexity: The integer defect","comments":"25 pages, 6 tables","journal-ref":"Moscow J. Comb. Number Th. 8 (2019) 193-217","doi":"10.2140/moscow.2019.8.193","report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Define $\\|n\\|$ to be the complexity of $n$, the smallest number of ones\nneeded to write $n$ using an arbitrary combination of addition and\nmultiplication. John Selfridge showed that $\\|n\\|\\ge 3\\log_3 n$ for all $n$,\nleading this author and Zelinsky to define the defect of $n$, $\\delta(n)$, to\nbe the difference $\\|n\\|-3\\log_3 n$. Meanwhile, in the study of addition\nchains, it is common to consider $s(n)$, the number of small steps of $n$,\ndefined as $\\ell(n)-\\lfloor\\log_2 n\\rfloor$, an integer quantity. So here we\nanalogously define $D(n)$, the integer defect of $n$, an integer version of\n$\\delta(n)$ analogous to $s(n)$. Note that $D(n)$ is not the same as $\\lceil\n\\delta(n) \\rceil$.\n  We show that $D(n)$ has additional meaning in terms of the defect\nwell-ordering considered in [3], in that $D(n)$ indicates which powers of\n$\\omega$ the quantity $\\delta(n)$ lies between when one restricts to $n$ with\n$\\|n\\|$ lying in a specified congruence class modulo $3$. We also determine all\nnumbers $n$ with $D(n)\\le 1$, and use this to generalize a result of Rawsthorne\n[18].\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 20 Apr 2018 03:53:14 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 28 Apr 2018 07:30:50 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 2 Aug 2018 03:07:14 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Fri, 3 Aug 2018 00:31:10 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-08-14"}
